55bed-3 | 2026-06-03T08:44:32Z | session:55bedfc3-dd9e-4b1c-b7d7-cea0c699d4d1 | ### 1. Core ML sentence transformer (~23 MB) \n Convert `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` from HuggingFace → Core ML via `coremltools`. You get 384-dim sentence embeddings that run on the Neural Engine. \n  \n - **Best quality/size ratio** for RAG \n - Runs fully on-device with Apple hardware acceleration \n - No extra runtime — Core ML is built into iOS \n - Conversion is one-time offline tooling step; model ships as a `.mlpackage` [...] **Core ML MiniLM** if you're okay with the Swift/Core ML boundary for this one task — it's the fastest path and gets Neural Engine acceleration. **ONNX via `ort` in Rust** if you want embeddings to stay in the kernel alongside the other retrieval logic. The model file is the same 23 MB either way. [...] **Core ML — yes, natively.** It's been on iPhone since iOS 11. MiniLM converted to `.mlpackage` runs on iPhone without any changes, and gets Neural Engine acceleration on A12+ (so any iPhone XS or newer). This is the most battle-tested path — there are production apps doing exactly this. [...] **Main tradeoff:** embedding lives in Swift/Core ML, outside the Rust kernel — which breaks your pattern of business logic in Rust. [...] **Short answer:** Core ML is the right call for iPhone. Same 23 MB model, Neural Engine acceleration, zero cross-compilation headaches, and it just works. The ONNX/Rust path is appealing architecturally but the iOS build complexity isn't worth it for this specific piece — embedding generation is more of an infrastructure concern than business logic anyway.
